<h3><font color="blue">Chapter 11</font></h3>
<h1>Temporal Models</h1>
</center>
<hr size=3>

<h2>1. Languaged-Based Model</h2>
<h3>
<ul>
<img src="blue.gif"> Add extension to language to support synchronization<br>
<img src="blue.gif"> Example : Communicating Sequential Processing (CSP) , Restricted Blocking <br>
<img src="blue.gif"> <i>Advantage</i> : Lead to implementation <br>
<img src="blue.gif"> <i>Disadvantage</i> : Hard to visualize and difficult to verify. <br>
</ul>
</h3>

<p>
<h2>2. Petri-Net Model</h2>
<table border=5 cellpadding=5>
<tr align=center>
<td> <b>Type</b>
<td> <b>Advantage</b>
<td> <b>Disadvantage</b>
</tr>

<tr>
<td> <b>OCPN (Object Composition Petri Net)
<td> Capture all the necessary temporal relations.
<td> Lack capabilities to specify communication requirements and control
    function for distributed composition of multimedia documents
</tr>

<tr>
<td> <b>G-Net </b>
<td> Allow specifications of communication primitives and type of connections
	that can be established among communication sites.
<td> Over simplified and does not facilitate generation of multimedia documents
</tr>

</table>
<p>

<h3>
<ul>
<img src="green.gif"> <a href="petri.jpg">Figure 11-5</a> shows an OCPN with QOP parameters. <br>
</ul>
</h3>

<h2>3. User Interaction Models</h2>
<h3>
<ul>
<img src="red.gif"> The means to manipulate or control the presentation of temporal specification <br>
<img src="red.gif"> Example : reduce or increase the speed of multimedia presentation.
</ul>

</h3>

